Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setPinConstraint(25.10)                                setPinConstraint(25.10)

Name
       setPinConstraint  -  Sets  the constraints for partition pins or an I/O
       pins

Syntax
       setPinConstraint

       [-help]

       {[-global | -cell <cell_name> | -matchEarlyGlobalRoute ]

        [-global | -pin <pin_name_list>| -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>} | -side  <side>
       <_name> | -matchEarlyGlobalRoute ]

        [-global | -layer {<layer_id_or_name_list>} | -loc {<x> <y> z}]

        [-global  |  -loc  {<x>  <y> z} | -edge <edge_numbers> | -corner <cor-
       ner_number>]

        [[-pin <pin_name_list> [-loc {<x > <y> z}] [-edge <edge_numbers>]] |

        [[-loc {<x> <y> z}] [-edge <edge_numbers>]] |

        [-corner_to_pin_distance <pin_distance> [-corner <corner_number>]]]

        [{-pin <pin_name_list> | -pinTemplate {<layer_id_or_name_list>}}

        [-use_min_width_as_depth | -depth <depth>] [-width <width>]]

        [[-layer {<layer_id_or_name_list>} [-side <side_names>]] |

       [-pinTemplate {<layer_id_or_name_list>} [-use_min_width_as_depth ]]]

       [-spacing <spacing> [-area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}] [-side <side_names>]]}

       [-depth <depth> [-special_wire ]]

       Sets the constraints for partition pins or an I/O  pins.  You  can  use
       this  command  before assigning pins. The constraints can be applied on
       three different levels:

              * Global pin constraint

              * Cell specific pin constraint

              * Pin specific constraint

       If no pin specific constraints exist, then the cell  level  constraints
       are  applied.  If  cell  specific pin constraints are not defined, then
       global constraints are applied.

       Note: To retrieve the pin constraints specified  using  the  setPinCon-
       straint  command, use the getPinConstraint  command. To remove the con-
       straints for a partition pin, use the unsetPinConstraint command.

Parameters
       -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Specifies an area overlapping with partition where spacing  con-
              straint.

              Data_type: rect, optional

       -cell <cell_name>
              Specifies  the  name  of  the module. The module name is not re-
              quired if the command is run on a top-level module. You can  use
              wildcards (*?) with this parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -corner <corner_number>
              Specifies the corner of the partition block.

              Data_type: int, optional

       -corner_to_pin_distance <pin_distance>
              Specifies the corner to pin distance in tracks.

              Data_type: int, optional

       -depth <depth>
              Specifies the pin depth in microns.

              Data_type: float, optional

       -edge <edge_numbers>
              Specifies  the  integer  value  where edge numbering starts from
              lower-left corner of a partition clock-wise.

              Edge 0 is the edge that has the smallest y value.

              You can set multiple sides in the -edge option. This allows  you
              to set multiple sides in a rectilinear design.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -global
              Specifies  that  the  global constraints for spacing, width, and
              depth to be honored.

              Note: If no pin specific constraints exist, then the cell  level
              constraints  are  applied.  If cell specific pin constraints are
              not defined, then global constraints are applied.

              For example, the following command  specifies  that  the  global
              constraints are to be honored.

              setPinConstraint  -global -spacing 2 -width 2 -pinTemplate { 2 3
              4 }

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each

              setPinConstraint parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man setPinConstraint

       -layer {<layer_id_or_name_list>}
              Specifies the metal layers for the partition pin. If you specify
              multiple  layers, separate the layer names with a space. In this
              case, the command will constrain the pin to one of the specified
              layers.

              Notes:

              * This parameter does not restrict the pin to a location on  the
                layer.  If you want to restrict a pin on a particular location
                on a particular layer, use the -loc parameter instead.

              * The -layer parameter cannot be used with the -loc parameter.

              * The -layer parameter cannot be used with the -spacing  parame-
                ter.

              * Layers  can be specified using the LEF layer names or layer ID
                numbers.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -loc {<x><y z>}
              Specifies the x and y locations and z layer  ID  number  of  the
              partition  pin.  The x and locations are calculated with respect
              to the distance in microns from the lower  left  corner  of  the
              module.  The layer number specified should be a preferred layer.
              Otherwise, the command will move the pin to a  preferred  layer.
              For  example,  -loc  {10  12 7} specifies that the pin should be
              constrained to a location 10 microns on the x axis  and  12  mi-
              crons on the y axis from the lower left corner of the partition.
              on layer Metal7.

              Notes:

              * If  the pin location as per the specified x and y locations is
                not on a track, the pin is snapped to the nearest track on the
                specified layer.

              * If you specify this parameter, the assigned pins have a Placed
                status.

              * The -loc parameter cannot be used with the -layer parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -matchEarlyGlobalRoute
              When specified, it changes the pin constraints to make them com-
              pliant with earlyGlobalRoute and does the  following  for  every
              partition:

              * Allows all layers from setDesignMode -topRoutingLayer to -bot-
                tomRoutingLayer.

              * Sets pin spacing as 1

              Note:  The  changes  in pin constraints impact the output of the
              pin assignment commands - assignPtnPin, assignIoPins, and  edit-
              Pin.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -pin<pin_name_list>
              Specifies  the  name of the partition pin. You can use wildcards
              (*?) with this parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -pinTemplate {<layer_id_or_name_list>}
              Specifies the metal layers for the  width,  depth,  and  spacing
              constraints at global level and cell level

              Data_type: string, optional

       -side <side> <_name>
              Specifies  name of the side. Valid values are { N S E W } or { L
              B T R } or all.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -spacing <spacing>
              Specifies the minimum spacing between pins in pin  pitch  value,
              that is, the distance between tracks.

              For  example, if you specify a value of 2, the minimum pin spac-
              ing will be equal to the distance between track 1 and track 3.

              Data_type: int, optional

       -special_wire
              Specifies the depth constraint to be set and honored for special
              wire pins. When -special_wire parameter is  specified  with  the
              -depth, -cell and -pinTemplate  parameters, it enables the depth
              on  desired  layers of specified cells to be honored for special
              wire pins by the partition command only.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -use_min_width_as_depth
              Minimum width should be used as the pin depth.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -width <width>
              Specifies the pin width in microns.

              Data_type: float, optional

Example
              * The following command specifies a width of 10 micrometers  for
                all  partition  pins in the partition sheet14. These pins will
                be placed either on layer 2 or on layer 4.

                setPinConstraint -cell sheet14 -pin * -layer {Metal2 Metal4}

              * The following commands set the pin width and  depth  of  layer
                Metal2 for partition cell ALU to 0.4 and 0.6 respectively.

                setPinConstraint -cell ALU -layer Metal2 -width 0.4

                setPinConstraint -cell ALU -layer Metal2 -depth 0.6

              * The following commands set the pin width of pin pGroup1 to 0.3
                and reset the pin depth of pin pGroup1 to default.

                setPinConstraint -cell ALU -pin pGroup1 -width 0.3

                unsetPinConstraint -cell ALU -pin pGroup1 -depth

                With this example, all the pins of pGroup1 will have the width
                0.3 and the default depth.

              * The following commands set the minimum pin spacing for top and
                bottom edge of partition cell ALU to 1 track.

                setPinConstraint -cell ALU -edge T -spacing 1

                setPinConstraint -cell ALU -edge B -spacing 1

              * The  following  command sets minimum pin spacing for all edges
                of partition cell TDSP to 3 tracks

                setPinConstraint -cell TDSP -all -spacing 3

              *

                The following command sets the sides, T and B, of layer 3  and
                5 of partition cell ptn4

                setPinConstraint -cell ptn4 -layer {3 5} -side {T B}

              *

                The  following  command  sets the edges, 2 and 0, of partition
                cell ptn4

                setPinConstraint -cell ptn4 -pin * -edge {2 0}

              * The following commands sets the pin depth of layer M5 for par-
                tition cell P to 0.3 using the -special_wire parameter so that
                it is honored only by the partition command.

                setPinConstraint -cell  P  -depth  .3  -pinTemplate  M5  -spe-
                cial_wire;

                partition

Related Information
